# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: first-hop-redundancy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] The **Common Address Redundancy Protocol** or **CARP** is a computer networking protocol which allows multiple hosts on the same local area network to share a set of IP addresses.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] Its primary purpose is to provide failover redundancy, especially when used with firewalls and routers.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] In some configurations, CARP can also provide load balancing functionality.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] CARP provides functionality similar to Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP) and to Cisco Systems' Hot Standby Router Protocol (HSRP).
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] It is implemented in several BSD-based operating systems and has been ported to Linux (ucarp).
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] If there is a single computer running a packet filter, and it goes down, the networks on either side of the packet filter can no longer communicate with each other, or they communicate without any packet filtering.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] If, however, there are two computers running a packet filter, running CARP, then if one fails, the other will take over, and computers on either side of the packet filter will not be aware of the failure, so operation will continue as normal.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] In order to make sure the new master operates the same as the old one, the packet filter used must support synchronization of state between the two computers.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] A group of hosts using CARP is called a "group of redundancy".
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] The group of redundancy allocates itself an IP address which is shared or divided among the members of the group.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] Within this group, a host is designated as "master".
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] The main host is that which "takes" the IP address.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] It answers any traffic or ARP request brought to the attention of this address.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] Each host can belong to several groups of redundancy.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] Each host must have a second unique IP address.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] A common use of CARP is the creation of a group of redundant firewalls.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] The virtual IP address allotted to the group of redundancy is indicated as the address of the default router on the computers behind this group of firewalls.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] If the main firewall breaks down or is disconnected from the network, the virtual IP address will be taken by one of the firewall slaves and the service availability will not be interrupted.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] In the late 1990s the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began work on a protocol for router redundancy.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] In 1997, Cisco informed the IETF that it had patents in this area and, in 1998, pointed out its patent on HSRP.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] Nonetheless, IETF continued work on VRRP.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] After some debate, the IETF VRRP working group decided to approve the standard, despite its reliance on patented techniques, as long as Cisco made the patent available to third parties under reasonable and non-discriminatory licensing terms.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] Cisco informed the OpenBSD developers that it would enforce its patent on HSRP.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] Cisco's position may have been due to their lawsuit with Alcatel.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] As Cisco's licensing terms prevented an open-source VRRP implementation, the OpenBSD developers began developing CARP instead.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] This made CARP fundamentally different from VRRP and ensured that CARP did not infringe on Cisco's patent.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] Later, it was integrated into FreeBSD (first released in May 2005 with FreeBSD 5.4), NetBSD and Linux (ucarp).
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] While Cisco's US patent expired in 2014, the two incompatible protocols continue to coexist.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] OpenBSD uses VRRP's protocol number and MAC addresses.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] The OpenBSD project requested unique numbers from the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) but was denied.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] To allocate numbers, IANA has several requirements.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] At the time, these were specified in RFC 2780.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] Requirements include participating in a collaborative, lengthy discussion process within the IETF and producing a detailed textual specification of the protocol.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] The OpenBSD developers met neither requirement.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] IANA had assigned protocol number 112 to VRRP (in 1998, via RFC 2338).
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] Protocol number 112 remains in use by VRRP.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] CARP also uses a range of Ethernet MAC addresses which IEEE had assigned to IANA/IETF for the VRRP protocol.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/common-address-redundancy-protocol] In spite of the overlap, it is still possible to use VRRP and CARP in the same broadcast domain, as long as the VRRP group ID and the CARP virtual host ID are different.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] In addition to being able to set priorities on different gateway routers, GLBP allows a weighting parameter to be set.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] Based on this weighting (compared to others in the same virtual router group), ARP requests will be answered with MAC addresses pointing to different routers.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] Thus, by default, load balancing is not based on traffic load, but rather on the number of hosts that will use each gateway router.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] By default, GLBP load balances in round-robin fashion.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] GLBP elects one AVG (Active Virtual Gateway) for each group.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] Other group members act as backup in case of AVG failure.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] In case there are more than two members, the second best AVG is placed in the Standby state and all other members are placed in the Listening state.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] This is monitored using hello and holdtime timers, which are 3 and 10 seconds by default.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] The elected AVG then assigns a virtual MAC address to each member of the GLBP group, including itself, thus enabling AVFs (Active Virtual Forwarders).
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] Each AVF assumes responsibility for forwarding packets sent to its virtual MAC address.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] There could be up to four AVFs at the same time.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] By default, GLBP routers use the local multicast address 224.0.0.102 to send hello packets to their peers every 3 seconds over UDP 3222 (source and destination).
[src:first-hop-redundancy/gateway-load-balancing-protocol] Cisco implemented IPv6 support for GLBP in IOS release 12.2(33)SXI.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] In computer networking, the **Hot Standby Router Protocol** (**HSRP**) is a Cisco proprietary redundancy protocol for establishing a fault-tolerant default gateway.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] Version 1 of the protocol was described in RFC 2281 in 1998.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] Version 2 of the protocol includes improvements and supports IPv6 but there is no corresponding RFC published for this version.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] The protocol establishes an association between gateways in order to achieve default gateway failover if the primary gateway becomes inaccessible.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] HSRP gateways send multicast *hello* messages to other gateways to notify them of their priorities (which gateway is preferred) and current status (*active* or *standby*).
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] The primary router with the highest configured priority will act as a *virtual* router with a pre-defined gateway IP address and will respond to the ARP or ND request from machines connected to the LAN with a virtual MAC address.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] If the primary router should fail, the router with the next-highest priority would take over the gateway IP address and answer ARP requests with the same MAC address, thus achieving transparent default gateway failover.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] In the virtual MAC address, Xs represent the group ID in hex.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] HSRP is not a routing protocol as it does not advertise IP routes or affect the routing table in any way.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] HSRP has the ability to trigger a failover if one or more interfaces on the router go down.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] This can be useful for dual branch routers each with a single link back to the gateway.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] If the link of the primary router goes down, the backup router will take over the primary functionality and thus retain connectivity to the gateway.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] Version 2 of the protocol introduces stability, scalability and diagnostic improvements.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] It is not compatible with version 1 HSRP.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/hot-standby-router-protocol] There is no RFC for version 2 of the protocol.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] The process, which results in the proxy server responding with its own MAC address to an ARP request for a different IP address for proxying purposes, is sometimes referred to as *publishing*.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] The access router gives the dial-up nodes IP addresses in the range 192.168.0.128 – 192.168.0.254; for this example, assume a dial-up node gets IP address 192.168.0.254.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] without being wired into the Ethernet: the access router 'publishes' its own MAC address for 192.168.0.254.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] Now, when another node wired into the Ethernet wants to talk to the dial-up node, it will ask on the network for the MAC address of 192.168.0.254 and find the access router's MAC address.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] It will therefore send its IP packets to the access router, and the access router will know to pass them on to the particular dial-up node.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] All dial-up nodes therefore appear to the wired Ethernet nodes as if they are wired into the same Ethernet subnet.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] Certain applications may require multiple IP addresses on the server.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] Provided the addresses have to be from the 10.0.0.0/24 range, the way the problem is solved is through proxy ARP.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] /other virtual server environments) and 'published' on the 10.0.0.2 interface (although many operating systems allow direct allocation of multiple addresses to one interface, thus eliminating the need for such workarounds).
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] In this scenario a firewall can be configured with a single IP address.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] One simple example of a use for this would be placing a firewall in front of a single host or group of hosts on a subnetwork.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] A proxy ARP firewall can be placed in front of the server.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] In this way the server is put behind a firewall without having to make any further changes to the network.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] Disadvantage of proxy ARP include scalability as ARP resolution by a proxy is required for every device routed in this manner, and reliability, as no fallback mechanism is present, and masquerading can be confusing in some environments.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] Proxy ARP can create DoS attacks on networks if misconfigured.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/proxy-arp] Proxy ARP can hide device misconfigurations, such as a missing or incorrect default gateway.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The **Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol** (**VRRP**) is a computer networking protocol that provides for automatic assignment of available Internet Protocol (IP) routers to participating hosts.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] This increases the availability and reliability of routing paths via automatic default gateway selections on an IP subnetwork.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The protocol achieves this by the creation of virtual routers, which are an abstract representation of multiple routers, i.e. primary/active and secondary/Standby routers, acting as a group.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The virtual router is assigned to act as a default gateway of participating hosts, instead of a physical router.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] If the physical router that is routing packets on behalf of the virtual router fails, another physical router is selected to automatically replace it.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The physical router that is forwarding packets at any given time is called the primary/active router.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] VRRP provides information on the state of a router, not the routes processed and exchanged by that router.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] Each VRRP instance is limited, in scope, to a single subnet.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] It does not advertise IP routes beyond that subnet or affect the routing table in any way.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] VRRP can be used in Ethernet, MPLS and Token Ring networks with Internet Protocol Version 4 (IPv4), as well as IPv6.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] A virtual router must use *00-00-5E-00-01-XX* as its media access control (MAC) address.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The last byte of the address (XX) is the virtual router identifier (VRID), which is different for each virtual router in the network.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] This address is used by only one physical router at a time, and it will reply with this MAC address when an ARP request is sent for the virtual router's IP address.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] Physical routers within the virtual router must communicate within themselves using packets with multicast IP address *224.0.0.18* and IP protocol number 112 for IPv4, or *ff02::12* and IP protocol number 112 for IPv6.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] Routers backing up a virtual router have a priority between 1 and 254, and the router with the highest priority will become the primary/active.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The default priority is 100; for the MAC address owner, the priority is always 255.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] A failure to receive a multicast packet from the primary/active router for a period longer than three times the advertisement timer causes the secondary/standby routers to assume that the primary/active router is dead.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The virtual router then transitions into an unsteady state and an election process is initiated to select the next primary/active router from the secondary/standby routers.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] This is fulfilled through the use of multicast packets.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] Secondary/standby router(s) are only supposed to send multicast packets during an election process.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] One exception to this rule is when a physical router is configured with a higher priority than the current primary/active, which means that on connection to the network it will pre-empt the primary/active status.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] This allows a system administrator to force a physical router to the primary/active state immediately after booting, for example when that particular router is more powerful than others within the virtual router.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The secondary/standby router with the highest priority becomes the primary/active router by raising its priority above that of the current primary/active.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] It will then take responsibility for routing packets sent to the virtual gateway's MAC address.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] In cases where secondary/standby routers all have the same priority, the secondary/standby router with the highest IP address becomes the primary/active router.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] All physical routers acting as a virtual router must be in the same local area network (LAN) segment.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] Communication within the virtual router takes place periodically.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] This period can be adjusted by changing advertisement interval timers.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The shorter the advertisement interval, the shorter the black hole period, though at the expense of more traffic in the network.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] Security is achieved by responding only to first hop packets, though other mechanisms are provided to reinforce this, particularly against local attacks.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The election process is made orderly through the use of skew time, derived from a router's priority, and used to reduce the chance of the thundering herd problem occurring during the election.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The skew time is given by the formula (256 − *Priority*) / 256 (expressed in milliseconds).
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] Secondary/standby router utilization can be improved by load sharing.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] Work on VRRP started in 1997 with a first draft published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] In 1998, the protocol was officially defined.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] VRRP is an open standard, but Cisco claimed that their Hot Standby Router Protocol (HSRP), a similar but proprietary protocol with essentially the same facility, is patented and licensed.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] However, in 2001, in reply to a direct request, Robert Barr of Cisco replied that they will not assert any patent claims unless someone tried to assert a claim against Cisco.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] IBM also claims covering patents and their statement is readable on the IETF webpage.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] The protocol was refined in 2004 as version 2.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] VRRP version 3, the current version, was published in 2010.
[src:first-hop-redundancy/virtual-router-redundancy-protocol] Mellanox offers MAGP, a proprietary protocol based on VRRP that allows active-active operation.
